The Observer pattern is a behavioral design pattern used to establish a one-to-many dependency between objects,
so that when one object (the subject) changes state,
all its dependents (observers) are automatically notified and updated.


Advantage	Description
ğŸ” Decoupling	Promotes loose coupling between the subject and observers.
ğŸ“¢ Automatic Notification	Observers are automatically notified of changes in the subject.
ğŸ”„ Scalable	Easy to add or remove observers at runtime without modifying the subject.
ğŸ§± Reusability	Reusable components since the subject and observers are independent.
ğŸ’¡ Real-time Update	Ideal for applications requiring real-time data updates (e.g., dashboards, stock tickers).